  <h2>Michigan Garden Timing Notes</h2>

  <p>
    Michigan’s growing season is heavily influenced by the surrounding Great Lakes.
    Large bodies of water moderate temperature swings, which often delays spring warming
    but can extend the growing season later into fall. This lake influence creates
    meaningful differences in frost timing and heat accumulation across the state.
  </p>

  <p>
    Because of this variability, successful planting decisions in Michigan usually depend
    on how well crop maturity matches the seasonal heat available in your specific region.
  </p>

  <h3>1) The Great Lakes moderate frost timing</h3>

  <p>
    Water warms and cools more slowly than land. In spring, this can keep nearby areas
    slightly cooler, which sometimes delays soil warming and early planting.
    In fall, however, the lakes release stored heat that can delay frost compared to
    inland locations.
  </p>

  <p>
    Gardens near Lakes Michigan, Superior, or Huron often experience a longer frost-free
    window than inland regions. These lake-moderated microclimates are one reason Michigan
    can support fruit crops that struggle farther inland.
  </p>

  <h3>2) Northern vs southern Michigan growing seasons</h3>

  <p>
    Michigan spans several climate zones. Southern parts of the state typically accumulate
    more growing degree days and maintain longer frost-free periods. Northern Michigan
    has shorter seasons and earlier fall frost, even though summer daylight is longer.
  </p>

  <p>
    This difference explains why crop maturity recommendations often vary between the
    northern and southern parts of the state.
  </p>

  <h3>3) Summer heat drives most crop development</h3>

  <p>
    As in most northern climates, the majority of Michigan’s heat accumulation occurs
    during June and July. Warm-season crops like tomatoes, peppers, and sweet corn
    do most of their development during this mid-summer period.
  </p>

  <p>
    Crops planted early enough to take advantage of peak summer heat typically ripen
    reliably. Later plantings often struggle once nights begin cooling in late August.
  </p>

  <h3>4) Late-season cooling slows ripening</h3>

  <p>
    Even before the first frost arrives, overnight temperatures start trending downward
    as summer transitions toward fall. This cooling reduces growing degree day accumulation
    and slows the ripening of fruiting crops.
  </p>

  <p>
    For this reason, planting decisions later in the season usually depend less on
    frost-free days and more on how much heat remains before development slows.
  </p>

  <p class="small muted" style="margin:0.5rem 0 0 0;">
    Use the frost timing and remaining seasonal heat data above as your baseline,
    then compare crop maturity requirements with the remaining growing degree days
    available for your location.
  </p>
